@node "Icons" "Icons"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Magnum Opus 3 Icons.@{fg text}@{bg back}

 While I don't profess to be a great artist, like many others over time I
became fed up with trying to find a specific icon I liked and ended up
making some of my own. However, don't expect a full set of icons from me as
I have neither the time or inclination plus there are plenty of fantastic
icon sets available on the Aminet. All of the included icons use a palette
supplied with Magnum Opus called @{" colours." link "Installation" 100} This is similar the to that of
the popular Magic Workbench 2. During the construction of these icons I came
upon an undocumented feature of the IconInfo. See @{" Hidden Functions. " link "Hidden Functions" 0} Incase
you're interested I now use Personal Paint V7.1 with the new
"personal_io_icon.library" V5.9c by Elmar Plischke to produce icons. This
new library can be found on Aminet (pio_icon.lha biz/cloan CD22) and comes
highly recommended.

 When using Opus Magellan to replace icons you will be given the various
options for replacing, select "All" this will ensure that there is no
problems with the wrong default tooltypes etc.


 @{fg shine}def_Drawer.info@{fg text}
 Fed up with the standard Magic Workbench drawer icon that everyone seems to
use ? Don't want to pay the shareware fee ? Then this is the icon for you
and is totally FREE. It is exactly the same size but that's where the
similarity ends. You may want to install this as your default drawer icon
for each new one you create. To do this just copy it to ENVARC:Sys/

 @{fg shine}def.Guide.info@{fg text}
 This has proved to be my most popular icon and is also my favourite. Amiga
Format has been using this for some of the AmigaGuide files on their CD ROM
coverdisks. While I have no objection to this, I wish they'd leave my
copyright notice in the tooltype. Even worse on several occasions I've even
found that the tooltype message credits someone else as the author !!. It's
NOT, it's by me Richard Lane ˋ 1996-98. See separate @{" copyright " link "Copyright" 0} notice and
@{" Hidden Functions." link "Hidden Functions" 0} The "All" option should have been selected when replacing
the icon with mine.

 @{fg shine}def.PPGuide.info@{fg text}
 The same as the above but this one has a different default tooltype for use
with the @{" PowerPacked, Guide " link "PowerPacked data filetypes" 0} filetype.

 @{fg shine}def.Doc.info@{fg text}
 This is a miniature of the PPMore program that I'm sure everybody must have
seen. It is exactly the same size as the "def.Guide.info" so should look
good in a drawer full of documents.

 @{fg shine}def.PaintLayer.info@{fg text}
 For use with the @{" Photogenics, Paint Layer " link "Photogenics Filetypes" 0} filetype.

 @{fg shine}def.Picture.info@{fg text}
 You can use this one for a variety of different picture filetypes.

 @{fg shine}def.24Picture.info@{fg text}
 Slightly different version of the above to make it easy to spot 24 bit
pictures.

 @{fg shine}def.LhA.info@{fg text}
 Can be used with both LZX & LhA or any other archive filetype you want.

 @{fg shine}def.mod.info@{fg text}
 I tried really hard to make a decent icon for music modules, but as you can
see from this I failed miserably.

 @{fg shine}def.installer.info@{fg text}
 My own icon for use with installer scripts, much better than the default
one.

 @{fg shine}AppIcon.info@{fg text}
 A default icon for Opus Magellan when iconified that matches the style of
my hard drive icons.


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Disk_Icons. @{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{fg shine}HD.Disk.info@{fg text}
 This is the icon I've used as my own Hard Drive partition icon for years.

 @{fg shine}HD2.Disk.info@{fg text}
 Just an enhanced 8 colour version of the above that I made when I got a
second hard drive so I could differentiate which partitions were on what
physical device.

 @{fg shine}ZIP.Disk.info@{fg text}
 Though I don't possess one of the Iomega ZIP drives (yet) here's one you
might like to use if you do.

 @{fg shine}Quantum.Disk.info@{fg text}
 This new was done for all us lucky Quantum hard disk owners.

 @{fg shine}Quantum.Black.info@{fg text}
 The second one of the new design. This is the start of another project of
mine in which I'll be making a whole series of disk icons based on this new
design as I've already started on a few others.

 @{fg shine}HD.Black.info@{fg text}
 I was after a new look for my drive icons as I'd become bored of the one I
had been using for years and this is the result of much experimentation.

 @{fg shine}CDdrive.info@{fg text}
 A matching drive icon for CD's that can be used with various utilities that
replace CD icons.

..
@endnode

@node "Button Banks" "Button Banks"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Buttons.@{fg text}@{bg back}

 I'm sure you will already have a number of buttons on your own installation
of Directory Opus Magellan to do all manner of things. In this new release
of Magnum Opus I have included a few of my own that I hope you will find
useful.


 @{fg shine}Version.@{fg text}
 This button uses the same method for displaying a version string as used in
the @{" AmigaDOS.library " link "AmigaDOS.Library" 0} filetype, go to this for further details. This button
can be used for any other file that contains a standard version string. If
nothing, or odd results are displayed then the selected file(s) do not
contain a normal standard version string.

 @{fg shine}LZX add@{fg text}
 After seeing many attempts at providing a button to create or add files to
an @{" LZX Archive " link "LZX, archive" 0} they all had various failings of which there were too many
to go into here (including those supplied with Opus Magellan). This button
will make or add to an existing archive ALL files and/or directories
selected. If you have experienced problems with other LZX add buttons try
this one.

 @{fg shine}LZX add -9 MAX@{fg text}
 Exactly the same as the above but this one uses the maximum compression
possible. It is a lot slower and therefore is recommended for those archives
you intend to distribute or for long term archiving purposes.

 @{fg shine}LhA add@{fg text}
 As with the LZX add button this fixes the failings of ALL the other LhA add
buttons (including those supplied with Opus Magellan). In particular it
fixes a bug with the last available evaluation version of LhA V1.38.  This
makes the directory name come out in lower case but leaves files and icons
OK. Now the directories are all in their correct case. It also stops the LhA
program is being invoked several times when archiving large amounts of
files, it's also faster because of this.

 @{fg shine}XFD Decrunch@{fg text}
 Though all the packed filetypes that can be successfully be unpacked by
using the additional filetype popup menu item. This button will unpack as
many as selected in the source lister in one go.

..
@endnode

@node "Screen-back.dopus5 module" "Screen-back.dopus5 module"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Screen-back.dopus5 @{fg text}@{bg back} @{fg shine}ARexx module.@{fg text}

 Thanks to the example in the manual, I have made this small ARexx module
that let's you send the Directory Opus screen to the back if like me you use
it on it's own screen. This can be handy for those programs such as Ed &
FinalWriter V5 that insist on opening on Workbench if you don't have the
"default Pubscreen" menu item checked. This module adds the Screen_Back
function to the built in Directory Opus commands and makes it available for
use in other buttons and filetypes.

 This module superseeds the old Arexx script "Back.DOpus5" supplied with
Magnum Opus v1.0. It will be removed by the installation script of this
version.

..
@endnode

@node "FAQ" "FAQ"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1  @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Frequently Asked Questions.@{fg text}@{bg back} 

 Everything you should need to know to install and use Magnum Opus 3 is
explained in the @{" Installation " link "Installation" 0} & @{" Filetypes Overview " link "Filetypes Overview" 0} pages or in the
relevant @{" filetype page. " link "Filetypes_Index" 0} However, I am including here some of the various
questions that other users have asked me in the hope that it answers any
other questions you may have. If you still have any questions on the use of
Magnum Opus then please contact @{" me." link "Author Information" 0} 

 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  Why does Directory Opus take longer to load than it did before ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  This is because it loads the filetypes into memory and there are now
far more than before. The only way to speed things up without removing any
of the filetypes is to get a faster hard drive and/or processor. I hope you
will agree this extra few seconds wait is worth the improvements.


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  A number of program configuration and/or preferences files are not
recognised, why ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  The only types of these files I will support are where a program can
save and load files for different sets of preferences or configurations, as
is the case with the @{" Workbench, Prefs " link "Workbench Pref" 0} filetypes. I see no point in making
a filetype of which there will only ever be one on a users system.
Furthermore, these solitary files normally have names that are self
explanatory, for example "VirusZ_II.Prefs". 


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  I would like a filetype that recognises a particular filetype but I
cannot get the built in filetype editor to make one that gives accurate
results. 

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  The filetype editor in Opus Magellan is certainly an improvement over
previous versions but it does have limitations. If a file is a datatype or
IFF format then its quite good, though not always perfect. As it only uses
the first 16 bytes of a file for comparison and does not look any further
for a match, this is not always enough for many filetypes. There is also the
limitation in that it can not spot matching strings at different offsets.
Sometimes as is the case with many packed file format variations it needs
several matching strings to guarantee correct recognition. If you are having
difficulty creating a filetype the easy answer is to contact @{" me " link "Author Information" 0} and I will
be able to advise you if it's possible. I have looked at creating many
filetypes for all sorts of files NOT included in Magnum Opus. If it's one
I'm not aware of then I may be able to create one for you and also include
it in the next version for the benefit of others.


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  In Magnum Opus V2.1 you said you would be including a set of toolbar
buttons that use the @{" NewIcons " link "NewIcons Icon" 0} format, where are they ? 

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  Since V2.1 there has been a number of Newicon toolbar button packages
appearing that are very good. I now feel that there is no point in creating
another set, so for the foreseeable future I do not plan to make any. If you
would like me to make a set then please get in touch.


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  Why don't I have any "filetype popup menus" when using a lister in name
mode ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  Make sure that in the Environment Editor in Lister Options that the
"Name Mode PopUp" is checked. Don't forget to then click the save button.


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  Why don't you make the Magnum_Opus.Guide into @{" html " link "HTML, text" 0} pages that can be
read using a Web browser?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  One of the main reasons being that not every Amiga user has a powerful
CPU and lots of memory. Try running Opus Magellan and a web browser on a
68020 with 4mb of fast ram then you'll see what I mean. For the moment the
AmigaGuide documentation does everything that's needed, and every Amiga
owner using Workbench 3.0/3.1 (probably 90% plus) already has Multiview on
their system. 

 In recent weeks I have looked at converting the Magnum_Opus.Guide into HTML
format. I've tried out several of the utilities that convert AmigaGuide to
HTML, the best so far being "GuideML" (GuideML.lha text/hyper CD26). While
this does a good basic job it would still need a lot of further work to get
it to a standard that I'd be happy with. For the moment I would rather spend
the time and effort on improving Magnum Opus. This does NOT mean that I have
totally ruled out  converting it to html. If you would prefer the
documentation in HTML as opposed to AmigaGuide then get in touch.  


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text}  Is it possible to link the built in Directory Opus help file with that
of Magnum Opus ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  Yes, this is possible and I have looked at doing this in the past. But,
there are a number of potential drawbacks to this. If in future versions of
the DOpus5.guide the nodes are renamed or changed then links may not work.
For the best integration I would also need to make a few changes to the
supplied DOpus5.guide. I would also need to include this changed version
with Magnum Opus. I don't expect for one moment that GP Software would be
too happy in me doing this. 


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text} Is there a web site for Magnum Opus ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text} Not at the moment. However, in the next few months I hope to get an
internet account setup, so keep a look out for the next version of Magnum
Opus which should have more details on this. 


 @{fg shine}Q:@{fg text} Just how many more filetypes do you intend to add ?

 @{fg shine}A:@{fg text}  At least another 1000. Seriously though I have no upper limit planned.

..
@endnode

@node "Hidden Functions" "Hidden Functions"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Undocumented Features.@{fg text}@{bg back}

 With almost any program there is usually a function that's not documented,
or some hidden message or just something silly that the author put in. Opus
Magellan has quite a number of these. Here's some that I have found, they
may only apply to the UK version V5.661 but try them yourself and see.


 Most of the hidden features that I mentioned in Magnum Opus versions 1 &
2.x have now become common knowledge thanks to the new manuals. I will
include these one again incase you haven't seen or used Magnum Opus before.
There are also some others I didn't know about that can be found on the
GPSoftware WEB page.


 While finishing off this AmigaGuide, I discovered one gem that I don't
believe has been documented before. Open up the CLI window of Opus Magellan.
@{" click here " rxs "ADDRESS DOPUS.1 command CLI"} or go to the "Opus" menu and select "Execute Command" and click
on the CLI button. Now type in "@{fg shine}help me eliza!@{fg text}" without the quotes, you
should then get a message "@{fg shine}How can I help you?@{fg text}". Now this is where the fun
begins. I spent an entire afternoon typing things in to see what response I
could get and was pleasantly surprised by the results. Who would have
thought you could have a conversation with a program. Try out some of these
words and phrases, again without the quotes.

 "opus" (there are at least five different responses to this)
 "sorry"
 (try a four letter swear word beginning with f)
 (and another one beginning with c)
 "I'm mad"
 "I want a PPC Amiga"
 "why did the author put you in here"
 "why did the chicken cross the road?"
 "Say, do you have any psychological problems?"

 These are just a few that work, try asking it things that contain why,
when, where, who, what, etc. To go back to normal operation just type in
"shut up". I would be very interested if someone finds something really
interesting.


 Another one I found was in the new internal @{" CLI " rxs "ADDRESS DOPUS.1 command CLI"} If you type in "Joshua"
you get the message "Greetings Professor Falken." Just incase you don't get
the joke try watching the old movie from the 1980's called "War Games."


 Has anyone noticed that in icon or icon action mode, when you drag a floppy
disk into a hard drive window, if that disk has its own icon (disk.info)
that this is used for the drawer icon ? If the floppy disk does not have its
own icon then like Workbench a default drawer icon is used.


 There are a number of environmental variables, most have been included in
the documentation or manuals, but some of these are not well known. I'm not
going to go into detail here as there is a good editor available for this
called Do5extPrefs by Jens Weyer that I would recommend that you get
(Do5extPrefs16.lha biz/dopus).


 If you select "Quit" from the Opus menu it displays a requester saying
"This will end your Directory Opus session." If you then select "Cancel"
sometimes you get another requester saying @{" Good :) " link "MO3Pic-02/main" 0} I'm not able to
determine the criteria that cause this to happen and I only discovered this
by chance. It took quite a while to get the screen grab of it.


 Page 58 in the V5.5 manual mentions about the shift click on the animation
in the "About" requester. But if you continue to hold the shift key and
click again there are three further pictures. One is Greg Perry and two of
others who unfortunately I don't know. If you leave the About requester on
screen after about 30 seconds you get a scrolling list of credits. Some
people have reported that they cannot get this to work. I have traced this
down to the Directory Opus screen which must be running in 16 or more
colours.


 Another one is in the Icon information window that I found by accident. If
on either a tool, project or drawer icon you type in the following

 "@{fg shine}£££ Icon by Richard Lane ¨¨¨@{fg text}"

 excluding the quotes as a tooltype, when you next select information on
this icon the title bar of the @{" icon information window " rxs "ADDRESS DOPUS.1 command IconInfo 'DOpus5:Icons/def.Guide'"} reads

 "@{fg shine}Icon : <filename> Author : Richard Lane@{fg text}".

 Capitalisation is important it must say "Icon by" NOT "Icon By" or "icon
by". The first three characters are produced using ALT zero and the last
three ALT nine on a UK keyboard. This is how Amiga Format managed to wrongly
credit some of my AmigaGuide icons.

..
@endnode

@node "Version History" "Version History"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version History.@{fg text}@{bg back} 

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 3.1a (Released 29 November 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Minor updates of the documentation for release on to Aminet. 


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 3.1 (Released 20, October 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back}
 @{i}I wanted to wait a while until the new version of Opus Magellan was
released before I put out a new version. But due to an error within the
Magnum_Opus.Guide that I was less than happy about, I decided to release
this new version. Think of this as an updated version 3.0 that includes most
of the current work in progress.  @{ui}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Discovered problem with the way Heddley stores its temporary files which
caused several pages in the Magnum_Opus.Guide to be scrambled. I've
@{" documented " link "MOG mess" 0} how to avoid this happening, which will be of interest to other
Heddley users.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated Magnum_Opus.Guide (V3.1).

 @{fg shine}ñ@{fg text} Included another 14 filetypes and updated a few others.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Included a new version of the Installer script (V1.7) that also does just
an update if version 3.0 has already been installed. Despite what the
documentation said in the previous release, I actually updated the installer
twice just before the final release. I also removed the version history text
from the @{" installer script " link "Installation History" 0} to a separate page within the
Magnum_Opus.Guide.


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 3.0 (Released 16, August 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back} 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Included another 85 filetypes.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated many filetypes for reliability and/or speed of recognition.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated and re-wrote a large amount of the Magnum_Opus.Guide (V3.0). 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Found bug in @{" AmigaDOS library " link "AmigaDOS.Library" 0} filetype when used with Workbench 3.0 and
documented why this was and how to fix it.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Corrected mistake in @{" CrunchMania Data Encrypted " link "CrunchMania Data" 0} recognition string. 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} revamped the @{" toolbar buttons " link "Installation" 91} and included a few new ones.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated Installer script (V1.6)

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Fixed problem with filetype names on systems using Zappo/Archos CD
drives. The filetypes are now stored in an @{" LhA Self-Extracting Archive." link "LhA Filetypes" 140}
This also greatly speeds up installation from floppy disk .

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} included an alternative set of @{" LhA " link "LhA Filetypes" 0} & @{" LZX " link "LZX, archive" 0} filetypes to use with Edmund
Vermeulen's @{" ArcDir V1.1." link "LhA-LZX_Filetypes-ArcDir" 0}


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 2.2 (Released 29, Sept 1997).@{fg text}@{bg back}
 @{i}This version is only a minor revision. I am currently working on Magnum
Opus V3.0 which will be available shortly and include loads of new, improved
& updated items).@{ui}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated and improved the installer script (V1.3) several times. 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated and slightly revised the Magnum_Opus.Guide, I also corrected some
spelling mistakes and minor cosmetic errors. 


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 2.1 (Released 8, June 1997).@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Added another 9 filetypes.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Updated AmigaGuide documentation.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Changed filetype priorities to speed up recognition.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Included an installer script. (V1.0)


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 2.0 (NOT released). @{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} 144 new filetypes added (Phew). 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} All filetypes checked in detail on the new version of Directory Opus
V5.5.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Changed those filetypes that called for a public screen of DOPUS.1 to
{Qs} for those people who use Directory Opus as a Workbench replacement.
This also fixes any problems if for whatever reason you happen to be running
more than one copy of Directory Opus .

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} AmigaGuide documentation partially rewritten and updated 

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} New Icons added.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Renamed some filetypes for consistency.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Discovered wrong recognition of @{" TakeTracker, module " link "TakeTracker, module" 0} and corrected it.

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Remade ALL of the toolbar button brushes into 8 colour ones as Directory
Opus V5.5 now remaps the colours when using more than an 8 colour screen.


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 1.1 (released 30, Aug 1996) @{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text}  Minor interim release that fixes the few minor compatibility problems
that came about when used with the newly released version 5.5 of Directory
Opus.


 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Version 1.0 (released 19, Aug 1996)@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} First public release. 

..
@endnode

@node "Installation History" "Installation History"
@{i}Magnum Opus Guide V3.1 @{ui}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} Magnum_Opus.Install version history.@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} V1.7 (7 October 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Moved the version history from the installer script to the
   Magnum_Opus.Guide.
 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Included section for quickly updating Magnum Opus V3.0 to V3.1. 

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} V1.6 (17 August 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back} @{i}last minute update released with Magnum Opus 3.0.@{ui}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Completely changed the way obsolete parts were removed.
 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Changed a few messages around to make things faster.

 @{fg shine}@{bg fill} V1.5. (16 August 1998).@{fg text}@{bg back}

 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Included installation of two button banks I nearly forgot about.
 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Removed the option (in expert mode) to select where to install filetypes
   to. This really didn't make sense.
 @{b}@{fg shine}ñ@{ub}@{fg text} Changed amount of free disk space checked for.
